{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01TrVx6yA4LfFgE5tnJQ14td","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me understand what's being asked:\n\n1. Generate exactly 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files\n2. Save to `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.24.txt`\n3. FILENAME RULES:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens or underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics\n   - Filename title must EXACTLY match main title in content (case-insensitive OK)\n\n4. RECIPE MIX: ~60% English, ~40% Polish. Variety of categories.\n\n5. AVOID these recipes (they already exist in the codebase)\n\n6. PATTERN REQUIREMENTS:\n   - 4 files with SPLIT_TITLE (title split across 2-4 lines)\n   - 4 files with NARRATIVE (3-7 lines of prose intro)\n   - 2 files with SIMPLE (basic OCR noise, may appear after page number)\n\n7. FILE LENGTH: 15-60 lines, spillover should be 40-60 lines\n\nLet me create 10 diverse recipes:\n\n**SPLIT_TITLE (4 files):**\n1. \"Pan Seared Scallops with Lemon Butter\" - split as \"Pan Seared Scallops / with Lemon Butter\"\n2. \"Croquettes with Mushroom Sauce\" - split across lines\n3. \"Grilled Swordfish with Garlic and Herbs\" - split\n4. \"Sernik z Owocami Leśnymi\" (Polish cheesecake) - split Polish title\n\n**NARRATIVE (4 files):**\n1. \"Baked Cod in Parchment\" - with cooking story\n2. \"Bigos Letni\" (Polish summer stew) - with narrative\n3. \"Tart z Owocami Sezonowymi\" (Seasonal Fruit Tart) - narrative\n\n\n4. \"Braised Lamb Shanks\" - cooking narrative\n\n**SIMPLE (2 files):**\n1. \"Roasted Vegetable Medley\" - with OCR noise\n2. \"Chlebek Żytni\" (Rye Bread) - with page headers and noise\n\nI need to verify the language distribution and category diversity. So far I have 6 English recipes and 4 Polish ones, which hits the target ratio. The categories span seafood, meat, vegetables, and baked goods. places, random numbers scattered throughout, formatting inconsistencies, strikethrough text, page numbers, and section headers. I'll create realistic OCR artifacts for each recipe file to simulate what would come from scanning actual documents.\n\nStarting with the Pan Seared Scallops recipe, I'm generating a file with typical OCR errors like misspelled words, awkward line breaks, and formatting issues that would naturally occur when scanning a printed recipe card.\n\nFor the Croquettes with Mushroom Sauce, the file shows the title split across multiple lines with cooking times partially cut off—common issues when OCR software encounters unusual text layouts or page boundaries. The prep and chill times are visible but the cook time gets interrupted, which I'll complete with the remaining details from the original document. milk while whisking constantly until thick (about 3 minutes).\n\nSauté the onion and chopped mushrooms separately until all moisture evaporates, roughly 8 minutes, then fold into the béchamel. Once cooled slightly, stir in egg yolks and parmesan, season with salt, pepper, and nutmeg, then spread onto parchment paper and refrigerate for 30 minutes. Shape into torpedo forms, dip in beaten egg, coat with panko, and deep fry at 350°F until golden on both sides, about 2 minutes total. For the sauce, sauté sliced mushrooms and garlic in butter, dust with flour and cook briefly, pour in beef broth and simmer, finish with sour cream and season to taste before serving.\n\nFor the swordfish, combine minced garlic, fresh herbs like rosemary and thyme, olive oil, lemon juice, and balsamic vinegar in a shallow dish. Pat the steaks dry, season lightly, and submerge in the marinade, coating both sides well. Allow to sit at room temperature for at least 30 minutes, or refrigerate up to 4 hours for deeper flavor. Heat the grill to medium-high (around 400°F) and oil the grates.\n\nPlace the swordfish on the grill and let each side cook 4-5 minutes until the flesh flakes easily—avoid moving it around so a golden crust can form. Once cooked through, transfer to a plate and brush with any leftover marinade. Serve alongside lemon wedges and fresh greens. The dish pairs well with roasted asparagus and fingerling potatoes, with a crisp white wine like Pinot Grigio or Sauvignon Blanc as the ideal accompaniment.\n\nSernik z Owocami Leśnymi is a Polish forest berry cheesecake requiring 20 minutes of prep, 45 minutes in the oven, and 3 hours to cool, yielding 8-10 servings. The base uses crushed cookies or graham crackers mixed with melted butter and sugar. The filling combines cottage cheese, softened butter, sugar, eggs, wheat flour, potato starch, and vanilla extract, with lemon zest and juice for brightness.\n\nFor the topping, fresh or frozen forest berries are sprinkled over the filling before baking. The process involves preheating the oven to 180°C, pressing the crumb mixture into the pan, blending the cheese filling ingredients sequentially, pouring it over the base, distributing the berries evenly across the surface, and baking for 45 minutes until set. been passed down through generations of home cooks and professional chefs alike. This elegant method requires minimal cleanup and delivers maximum flavor, as the fish gently steams in its own juices with vibrant vegetables.\n\nThe technique is straightforward but impressive—parchment packets seal in moisture and aromatics, creating a restaurant-quality dish at home. I need two cod fillets, mixed julienned vegetables, garlic, white wine, butter, fresh herbs like thyme and tarragon, lemon juice, and parchment paper. The whole process takes about 35 minutes total, with just 15 minutes of prep and 18-20 minutes in the oven. Albariño complements the delicate fish flavors without overwhelming them. Moving to the next dish, Bigos Letni is Poland's national stew, traditionally made with cabbage and meat but transformed seasonally. The summer version incorporates fresh seasonal vegetables and lighter meats, making it perfect for warm evenings.\n\nThe dish carries deep family memories and generational traditions. Prep takes 20 minutes with 40 minutes of cooking time for six servings. The base combines diced pork and chicken with sliced kielbasa, then builds with shredded leafy cabbage, chopped tomatoes, diced zucchini, onion, garlic, and tomato paste.\n\nThe broth, apple vinegar, sugar, bay leaf, and caraway seeds round out the flavors, seasoned with salt and pepper. Start by browning the pork and poultry in a large pot, add the kielbasa briefly, then sauté the onion and garlic until soft. Layer in the cabbage, tomatoes, zucchini, tomato paste and vinegar, then pour in the broth with bay leaf, caraway, salt and pepper to finish.\n\nSimmer for 35-40 minutes until the vegetables soften completely. Serve alongside rye bread and sour cream.\n\nSezonowy tart to klasyk europejskich piekarni—kruchy spód, kremowa warstwa mascarpone lub migdałowa pasta, i błyszczące świeże owoce na wierzchu. Piękno tego deseru polega na jego prostocie i jakości składników, które zmieniają się wraz z porami roku, tworząc nowe kombinacje smaków i barw z każdym sezonem. Przygotowanie zajmuje 30 minut, a chłodzenie 2 godziny, na 8-10 porcji. Do spodu potrzebna mąka pszenna, zimne masło, żółtko, cukier i sól, a do kremu mascarpone i cukier. Przenieść do formy tartów 9 cali i piec 15 minut przy 180°C. Przygotować krem z mascarpone, cukru pudru, miodu, wanilii i zeste cytryny, następnie rozłożyć go równomiernie na ostygniętej skorupce. Ułożyć świeże owoce w atrakcyjnym wzorze, pokryć je żelem owocowym rozcieńczonym wodą dla połysku, i schłodzić przez 2 godziny przed podaniem.\n\nBraised Lamb Shanks to danie dla chłodnych dni—mięso gotowane powoli do miękkości, aż oddziela się od kości w bogatym sosie. Ta tradycyjna technika kulinarna wymaga kilka godzin, ale rezultat to niezwykle soczyste, aromatyczne mięso, które rozpada się widelcem. Podawać z puree ziemniaczanym lub chlebem, aby wchłonąć każdą kroplę sosu. Przygotowanie zajmuje 15 minut, duszenie 3-3,5 godziny, porcji dla 4 osób. Składniki obejmują 4 golonki jagnięce po około 1,25 funta każda.\n\nDo przygotowania potrzebne są: oliwa z oliwek, duża cebula, marchew, seler, czosnek, czerwone wino, bulion, pasta pomidorowa, rozmaryn, tymianek, liście laurowe, pieprz i sól. Procedura zaczyna się od nagrzania piekarnika do 325°F i osuszenia golonki, które następnie rumieni się w oliwie ze wszystkich stron. Warzywa dodaje się do tego samego garnka i gotuje przez 8-10 minut, potem czosnek i pasta pomidorowa przez 2 minuty. Wino deglaziuje się, a następnie dodaje się mięso z powrotem wraz z bulionem i ziołami. Całość dusi się w piekarniku przez 3-3,5 godziny, aż mięso będzie bardzo miękkie. Na koniec golonki przenosi się na talerz, a sos przeciera się i podaje razem z warzywami.\n\nDla warzywa pieczonego przygotowuję cukinie, paprykę, grzyby, cebulę, marchew i czosnek. Wszystkie warzywa (oprócz czosnku) mieszam z oliwą, octem balsamicznym, włoskim przyprawami, solą i pieprzem, rozkładam na blasze i pieczę w 400°F przez 35-40 minut, mieszając w połowie czasu, aż warzywa będą miękkie i karmelizowane. Można dodać parmezanę i podawać ciepło lub w temperaturze pokojowej.\n\nDo chlebka żytnego potrzebne są: ciemna mąka żytnia, mąka pszenna, ciepła woda, sól i drożdże. Dać wzrastać przez 45 minut. Opryskać wodą, posypać kminikiem i porylować nożem przed pieczeniem. Piec w 220°C przez 35-40 minut aż chleb nabierze złotego koloru i będzie pity. Po upieczeniu ostudzić na siatce. Chleb zyskuje na aromacie następnego dnia i świetnie sprawdza się do żurku — przechowuje się 3-4 dni w worku chlebowym.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":88228,"cache_read_input_tokens":15568,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":88228},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1677a1a0-3dd2-4865